  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Revenues of the Priests. - These are summed up in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 18:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in these words, \"I give thee the keeping of My heave-offerings in all holy gifts for a portion, as an eternal statute.\" The notion of משׁמרת, keeping, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 12:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 16:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 16:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is defined in the second parallel clause as משׁחה, a portion (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The priests were to keep all the heave-offerings, as the portion which belonged to them, out of the sacrificial gifts that the children of Israel offered to the Lord. תּרוּמת, heave-offerings (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 25:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is used here in the broadest sense, as including all the holy gifts (kodashim, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 21:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") which the Israelites lifted off from their possessions and presented to the Lord (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 5:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Among these, for example, were, first of all, the most holy gifts in the meat-offerings, sin-offerings, and trespass-offerings (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 18:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 18:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The burnt-offerings are not mentioned, because the whole of the flesh of these was burned upon the altar, and the skin alone fell to the portion of the priest (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"From the fire,\" sc., of the altar. אשׁ, fire, is equivalent to אשּׁה ot , firing (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 1:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). These gifts they were to eat, as most holy, in a most holy place, i.e., in the court of the tabernacle (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which is called \"most holy\" here, to lay a stronger emphasis upon the precept. In the second place, these gifts included also \"the holy gifts;\" viz., (a) (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 18:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the heave-offering of their gifts in all wave-offerings (tenuphoth), i.e., the wave-breast and heave-leg of the peace-offerings, and whatever else was waved in connection with the sacrifices (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): these might be eaten by both the male and female members of the priestly families, provided they were legally clean (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".); (b) (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 18:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the gifts of first-fruits: \"all the fat (i.e., the best, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 45:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
